{
  "text": "Currently, photoreceptors utilized in the generation of optogenetic tools can be divided according to three main chromophores: phycocyanobilin (PCB), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) and flavin mononucleotide (FMN). PCB is a blue tetrapyrrole chromophore from cyanobacteria that acts as light energy acceptor in phycobiliproteins [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . FAD is a flavin conjugated with an adenosine diphosphate derived from riboflavins and associated with blue-dependent photoproteins [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . FMN, another blue light-absorbing chromophore also derived from riboflavins, is responsible for the conformational change occurring in phototropins, LOV-domains containing photo sensors [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Interestingly, there is a fourth category comprised of a family of photoreceptors reactive to ultraviolet light whose function is independent of a chromophore [CITATION_8] . Here, we will focus mainly on the PCB-dependent phytochrome PhyB [CITATION_9] , FDA-dependent cryptochromes (CRY2) [CITATION_10] , FMN-dependent LOV domains [CITATION_11] , and UVR8 [CITATION_12] photoreceptors because they are the most widely used for optical control of gene transcription ( Table 1) .",
